00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:28.770
So those have the same ranks.

00:07:28.770 --> 00:07:31.650
But I want to get
further than that.

00:07:31.650 --> 00:07:35.220
I want to find this.

00:07:35.220 --> 00:07:37.380
So how do I go?

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:40.820
How do I go forward
with that job

00:07:40.820 --> 00:07:43.350
to find the derivative
of the inverse?

00:07:43.350 --> 00:07:51.660
Well, I'm going to call
this a change in A inverse.

00:07:51.660 --> 00:07:56.015
And over here, I'll
have B will be--

00:07:58.810 --> 00:08:02.920
yeah, OK, let's see, am I right?

00:08:02.920 --> 00:08:03.670
Yeah.

00:08:03.670 --> 00:08:07.630
So B inverse will be--

00:08:07.630 --> 00:08:14.680
this is A plus delta A inverse.

00:08:14.680 --> 00:08:18.220
And this is-- well,
that's A minus B. So

00:08:18.220 --> 00:08:29.680
that's really minus delta A.
From A to B is the change.

00:08:29.680 --> 00:08:33.429
Here, I'm looking at the
difference A minus B.

00:08:33.429 --> 00:08:35.049
So it's minus a change.

00:08:35.049 --> 00:08:37.960
And here, I have A inverse.

00:08:37.960 --> 00:08:45.640
I haven't done anything
except to introduce this delta

00:08:45.640 --> 00:08:49.240
and get B out of it
and brought delta in.

00:08:49.240 --> 00:08:52.130
Now, I'm going to do calculus.

00:08:52.130 --> 00:09:00.220
So I'm thinking of B as
there's a sort of a delta t.

00:09:00.220 --> 00:09:04.370
And I'm going to divide
by both sides by delta t.

00:09:04.370 --> 00:09:05.830
I have to do this if I want--

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:14.840
and now, I'll let
delta t go to 0.

00:09:14.840 --> 00:09:17.030
So calculus appears.

00:09:19.790 --> 00:09:27.390
Finally, our-- I won't
say enemy calculus,

00:09:27.390 --> 00:09:31.730
