00:15:00.690 --> 00:15:01.860
Not usually.

00:15:01.860 --> 00:15:05.500
Of course, if the
matrix was symmetric,

00:15:05.500 --> 00:15:09.150
then A and A transpose
are just the same thing.

00:15:09.150 --> 00:15:13.620
So A transpose would
have that eigenvalue--

00:15:13.620 --> 00:15:14.160
eigenvector.

00:15:14.160 --> 00:15:17.850
But, generally, it has
a different eigenvector.

00:15:17.850 --> 00:15:22.890
And really to keep a sort
of separate from this one,

00:15:22.890 --> 00:15:24.530
let's call it y.

00:15:24.530 --> 00:15:26.970
It will have the
same eigenvalue.

00:15:26.970 --> 00:15:28.590
I'm going to call it y.

00:15:28.590 --> 00:15:33.760
But I'm going to make it a row
vector, because A transpose is

00:15:33.760 --> 00:15:34.270
what--

00:15:34.270 --> 00:15:36.340
instead of writing
down A transpose,

00:15:36.340 --> 00:15:39.130
I'm going to stay with
A, but put the eigenvalue

00:15:39.130 --> 00:15:40.240
on the left side.

00:15:40.240 --> 00:15:43.000
So here's is the eigenvalue--

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:48.260
eigenvector for A on the left.

00:15:48.260 --> 00:15:53.680
And it has the same eigenvalue
times that eigenvector.

00:15:53.680 --> 00:15:58.100
But that eigenvector is a
row eigenvector, of course.

00:15:58.100 --> 00:16:01.230
This is an equality
between rows.

00:16:01.230 --> 00:16:05.150
A row times my
matrix gives a row.

00:16:05.150 --> 00:16:08.450
So that's the eigenvalues of--

00:16:08.450 --> 00:16:10.210
and it has the same eigenvalues.

00:16:10.210 --> 00:16:14.650
So this is totally parallel
to that, totally parallel.

00:16:14.650 --> 00:16:17.770
And maybe sort of less--

00:16:17.770 --> 00:16:25.450
definitely less
seen, but it's just

00:16:25.450 --> 00:16:27.970
the same thing for A transpose.

00:16:27.970 --> 00:16:30.910
Everybody sees that if I
transpose this equation,

00:16:30.910 --> 00:16:33.400
then I've got something
that looks like that.

